    <!-- CHAPTER 5 -->
    <h2>CHAPTER 5: DATABASE DESIGN</h2>
    <h3>Database Schema</h3>
    <p>The database name used is <code>attendance_db</code>.</p>

    <h3>Table Structures</h3>
    <p><b>1. Table: users</b></p>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td>id</td><td>INT</td><td>Primary Key</td></tr>
        <tr><td>username</td><td>VARCHAR</td><td>Login ID</td></tr>
        <tr><td>password</td><td>VARCHAR</td><td>Hashed Password</td></tr>
        <tr><td>role</td><td>ENUM</td><td>'teacher' or 'student'</td></tr>
    </table>

    <p><b>2. Table: attendance</b></p>
    <table>
        <tr><th>Field</th><th>Type</th><th>Description</th></tr>
        <tr><td>id</td><td>INT</td><td>Primary Key</td></tr>
        <tr><td>student_id</td><td>INT</td><td>Link to student</td></tr>
        <tr><td>subject_id</td><td>INT</td><td>Link to subject</td></tr>
        <tr><td>date</td><td>DATE</td><td>Date of class</td></tr>
        <tr><td>status</td><td>ENUM</td><td>'present' or 'absent'</td></tr>
    </table>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- CHAPTER 6 -->
    <h2>CHAPTER 6: MODULE DESCRIPTION</h2>
    
    <h3>Login Module</h3>
    <p>This is the entry point. It accepts a username and password. The system checks the <code>users</code> table. If the role is 'teacher', it redirects to <code>teacher_dashboard.php</code>. If 'student', it goes to <code>student_dashboard.php</code>.</p>

    <h3>Admin Module</h3>
    <p>(Handled via database directly for this project scope) - Creates new users, courses, and subjects.</p>

    <h3>Teacher Module</h3>
    <p>Teachers can see the subjects assigned to them. They can select a subject, date, and period to mark attendance for all enrolled students.</p>

    <h3>Student Module</h3>
    <p>Students can view their profile, roll number, and course. The main feature is the "Total Percentage" card which tells them if they are eligible for exams.</p>

    <h3>Attendance Module</h3>
    <p>This is the core logic. It takes the input from the teacher (Present/Absent checkboxes) and inserts records into the MySQL database. It creates a new row for every student for that period.</p>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- CHAPTER 7 -->
    <h2>CHAPTER 7: USER INTERFACE DESIGN</h2>
    <p>The UI is designed using HTML and CSS. I have used the college color theme (Blue and White) to make it look professional.</p>

    <h3>Login Page</h3>
    <p>Has two buttons: "Faculty Login" and "Student Login". It uses a background image of the college campus.</p>

    <h3>Dashboard</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><b>Teacher Dashboard:</b> Shows cards for "Total Students" and "Total Classes".</li>
        <li><b>Student Dashboard:</b> Shows "Classes Attended", "Total Percentage", and "Exam Status" (Green for Eligible, Red for Shortage).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Attendance Entry Page</h3>
    <p>A simple list of students with checkboxes. The teacher just needs to uncheck the absent students and click "Submit".</p>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- CHAPTER 8 -->
    <h2>CHAPTER 8: IMPLEMENTATION</h2>
    
    <h3>Backend Implementation</h3>
    <p>The backend is written in <b>PHP</b>. I used <code>mysqli</code> for connecting to the database.</p>

    <h3>Database Connectivity</h3>
    <p>All database queries are executed using SQL.</p>
    <ul>
        <li><code>SELECT</code> is used to fetch login details and reports.</li>
        <li><code>INSERT</code> is used to save attendance.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Session Management</h3>
    <p>I used PHP Sessions (<code>session_start()</code>) to ensure security. If a user tries to open the dashboard without logging in, the system checks the session and redirects them back to the login page.</p>

    <div class="page-break"></div>

    <!-- CHAPTER 9 -->
    <h2>CHAPTER 9: TESTING</h2>
    
    <h3>Testing Strategy</h3>
    <p>I performed <b>Unit Testing</b> and <b>Integration Testing</b>. I tested each page separately to make sure there were no errors.</p>

    <h3>Test Cases</h3>
    <p><b>Test Case 1: Login</b></p>
